# User Management System - Spring Boot Backend

A RESTful API built with Spring Boot and H2 database for managing users. This backend serves the Android mobile application and any other clients.

## Features

- **Create Users** - Add new users via POST request
- **Read Users** - Fetch all users or specific user
- **Update Users** - Modify existing user information
- **Delete Users** - Remove users from database
- **Full REST API** - Comprehensive CRUD operations
- **In-Memory Database** - H2 for quick testing and development

## Technology Stack

- **Framework:** Spring Boot 3.x
- **Language:** Java 17
- **Database:** H2 (In-memory)
- **ORM:** Hibernate/JPA
- **Build Tool:** Maven
- **API:** REST
- **Libraries:** Lombok, Jackson

## Project Structure
```
user-management-backend/
├── src/
│   ├── main/
│   │   ├── java/com/example/userapi/
│   │   │   ├── User.java              - User entity (database model)
│   │   │   ├── UserRepository.java    - Database access layer
│   │   │   ├── UserService.java       - Business logic layer
│   │   │   ├── UserController.java    - REST API endpoints
│   │   │   └── UserManagementBackendApplication.java
│   │   └── resources/
│   │       └── application.properties - Configuration
│   └── test/
├── pom.xml                            - Dependencies
└── README.md
```

## Getting Started

### Prerequisites

- Java 17 or higher
- Maven 3.6 or higher
- Git

### Installation

1. **Clone the repository:**
```bash
git clone https://github.com/Hellooo-beep/user-management-backend.git
cd user-management-backend
```

2. **Build the project:**
```bash
mvn clean install
```

3. **Run the application:**
```bash
mvn spring-boot:run
```

The backend will start on: `http://localhost:8080`

### Verification

Once started, you should see in console:
```
Started UserManagementBackendApplication in X.XXX seconds
```

## API Endpoints

### Create User
```
POST /api/users
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "name": "Ritika Singh",
    "email": "ritika@example.com",
    "phone": "9876543210"
}

Response (201):
{
    "id": 1,
    "name": "Ritika Singh",
    "email": "ritika@example.com",
    "phone": "9876543210"
}
```

### Get All Users
```
GET /api/users

Response (200):
[
    {
        "id": 1,
        "name": "Ritika Singh",
        "email": "ritika@example.com",
        "phone": "9876543210"
    }
]
```

### Get User by ID
```
GET /api/users/1

Response (200):
{
    "id": 1,
    "name": "Ritika Singh",
    "email": "ritika@example.com",
    "phone": "9876543210"
}
```

### Update User
```
PUT /api/users/1
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "name": "Ritika Sharma",
    "email": "ritika.sharma@example.com",
    "phone": "9999999999"
}

Response (200):
{
    "id": 1,
    "name": "Ritika Sharma",
    "email": "ritika.sharma@example.com",
    "phone": "9999999999"
}
```

### Delete User
```
DELETE /api/users/1

Response (204): No Content
```

## Testing with Postman

1. Download Postman: https://www.postman.com/downloads/
2. Create requests using endpoints above
3. Test each operation:
   - POST to create user
   - GET to retrieve users
   - PUT to update user
   - DELETE to remove user

## Database

### H2 In-Memory Database

The application uses H2, a lightweight in-memory database.

**Advantages:**
- No installation needed
- Fast for development and testing
- Data resets when app restarts
- Perfect           ↓┌─────────────────────────────────────┐│   Service Layer (UserService)       │  Business Logic│   - Validates data                  ││   - Implements business rules       │└────────────────────────
